.SH NAME
dtterm \- Cde terminal emulator
.SH SYNOPSIS
.yS
dtterm
[\-options]
.yE
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f3dtterm\fP
client provides run time support of legacy applications
written for \f3ANSI X3.64-1979\fP and \f3ISO 6429:1992(E)\fP 
conformant character terminals such as the \f3DEC VT220\fP.
.P
The \f3dtterm\fP
client does not provide full \f3DEC VT220\fP terminal functionality.
The following \f3VT220\fP functionality is
not supported:
.VL 6
.LI \f3DECDWL\fP
Double-width, single-height text is not supported.
.LI \f3DECDHL\fP
Double-width, double-height text is not supported.
.LE
.P
.SH OPTIONS
The following options are available:
.VL 6
.LI \f3\-132\fP
Normally, \f3dtterm\fP ignores the \f3DECCOLM\fP escape sequence that
switches between 80 and 132 column mode.
This option causes \f3dtterm\fP to recognize the \f3DECCOLM\fP
escape sequence, and the \f3dtterm\fP window resizes appropriately.
.P
.LI \f3\+132\fP
This option causes \f3dterm\fP to ignore the \f3DECCOLM\fP escape sequence.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\-aw\fP
This option indicates that \f3dtterm\fP allows auto-wraparound.
This allows the cursor to automatically wrap to the beginning of the next
line when it is at the right-most position of a line and text is output.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\+aw\fP
This option indicates that \f3dtterm\fP does not allow auto-wraparound.
.P
.LI "\f3\-background\fP \f2background_color\fP"
This option specifies the background of the
terminal window as well as the default background \f3dtterm\fP uses for the
scroll bar and the X11 pointer cursor.
Under
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde, 
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE
this option defaults to either the primary colorset
background
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
(default) or select
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.\" (default)
pixel (see \f3\-bs\fP).
Without
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE
this option defaults to \f3*background/*Background\fP with an ultimate
fall back color of black.
.P
\f2background_color\fP  -  Describes the background color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-bd\fP \f2border_color\fP"
This option specifies the border color for all windows.
The shell widget's window border may not be visible when re-parenting window 
managers such as
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.Cm dtwm(1)
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" \f3vuewm(1X)\fP
and
.Cm mwm(1X)
are used.
The default is the color black.
.P
\f2border_color\fP - Describes the border color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-bg\fP \f2background_color\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-background\fP.
.P
\f2background_color\fP - Describes the background color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-bordercolor\fP \f2border_color\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-bd\fP.
.P
\f2border_color\fP - Describes the border color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-borderwidth\fP \f2border_width\fP"
This option specifies the border width of the shell widget's window.
This value may be overriden by re-parenting window managers such as
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.Cm dtwm 1
and
.Cm mwm 1X.
The default is 0.
.P
\f2border_width\fP - Specifies the width of the window border in pixels.
.P
.LI \f3\-bs\fP
This option specifies that the terminal window uses the Motif
select color instead of the background color for the terminal window's
background color.
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.\" This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\+bs\fP
This option specifies that the terminal window not use the Motif
select color instead of the background color for the terminal window's
background color.
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI "\f3\-bw\fP \f2border_width\fP"
This option is identical to \f3-borderwidth\fP above.
.P
\f2border_width\fP - Specifies the width of the window border in pixels.
.P
.LI \f3\-C\fP
This option specifies that output directed at 
\f3/dev/console\fP
be directed instead to the terminal window.
It is provided as a way to prevent output that would normally be displayed on the
ITE from stepping on the X server's display.
It is not provided as a general purpose mechanism to direct the output from
an arbitrary system's \f3/dev/console \fP to an arbitrary X server.
Ownership of, and read-write permission for, \f3/dev/console \fP
is required to redirect console output.
The default is False.
.P
.LI "\f3\-display\fP \f2display_name\fP"
This option specifies the X11 display server \f3dtterm\fP uses.
This defaults to the \f3DISPLAY\fP environment variable.
.P
\f2display_name\fP - Specifies the X11 display \f3dtterm\fP connects to.
.P
.LI "\f3\-e \fP \f2program_argument ...\fP"
This option specifies an executable program and any command line arguments
\f3dtterm\fP invokes as a subprocess when \f3dtterm\fP is started.
It must be the last option on the command line.
.P
\f2program_argument ...\fP - Specifies the program \f3dtterm\fP executes and any command
line arguments.
.P
.LI "\f3\-fb\fP \f2fontset\fP"
This option specifies an \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses when displaying bold terminal
text.
The \f3XFontSet\fP should be specified as a Motif
.Fn XmFontList 3X.
The terminal emulator supports only character- or mono-spaced fonts.
The behavior, when using proportional fonts, is undefined.
The terminal emulator generates a default bold font based on the \f3XLFD\fP
name of the \f3userFont\fP.
If that font is not available, \f3dtterm\fP generates bold text
by overstriking (with a one pixel offset) the \f3userFont\fP.
.P
\f2fontset\fP - Specifies the bold terminal \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-fg\fP \f2foreground_color\fP"
This option specifies the foreground color of the terminal window as
well as the default foreground color \f3dtterm\fP uses for the scroll bar and the
for the X11 pointer cursor.
Under
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this option defaults to the 
primary color set foreground pixel.
Without
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this option defaults to \f3*foreground\fP/\f3*Foreground\fP 
with an ultimate fall back color of white.
.P
\f2foreground_color\fP - Specifies the foreground color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-fn\fP \f2fontset\fP"
This option specifies an \f3XFontSet\fP to be used when displaying terminal text.
It should be specified as a Motif
.Fn XmFontList 3X.
Only character- or mono-spaced fonts are supported.
The behavior, when using proportional fonts, is undefined.
This font is not used to display non-terminal text (such as menu bar, popup menus, 
or dialogs).
The default uses the \f3XmNtextFontList\fP value of the parent bulletin 
board (see
.Fn XmBulletinBoard 3X)
in the same manner as the
.Fn XmText 3X
widget.
.P
\f2fontset\fP - Specifies the terminal \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-font\fP \f2fontset\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-fn\fP above.
.P
\f2fontset\fP - Specifies the terminal \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-foreground\fP \f2foreground_color\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-fg\fP above.
.P
\f2foreground_color\fP - Specifies the foreground color \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-geometry\fP \f2geometry_string\fP"
This option
specifies the terminal window's preferred size and position.
Width and height are expressed in characters.
The default size is 24 lines of 80 characters each.
There is no default position.
.P
\f2geometry_string\fP - Specifies the terminal geometry \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI \f3\-help\fP
Displays a message summarizing \f3dtterm\fP usage.
.LI \f3\-iconic\fP
This option specifies that the terminal emulator initially be displayed in an
iconified state.
.P
.LI \f3\+iconic\fP
This option specifies that the terminal emulator initially be displayed
as a normal window.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\-j\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP uses jump scrolling.
Under jump scrolling, the screen may be scrolled more than one line at a time.
This provides for faster screen updates when multiple lines of text are sent to the terminal.
The maximum number of lines that may be
jump scrolled is limited to the number of lines in the terminal window.
The termminal emulator guarantees that all lines are displayed.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\+j\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP not use jump scrolling.
.LI \f3\-kshMode\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP enable ksh mode.
Under ksh
mode, a key pressed with the extend modifier bit set generates an
escape character followed by the character generated by the un-extended
keystroke.
This option is provided to use with emacs and the emacs
command line editor mode of
.Cm ksh 1
or
.Cm ied 1.
This option conflicts with the
normal meta key use for generating extended single byte
characters and for generating multi-byte Asian characters.
.P
.LI \f3\+kshMode\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP not enable ksh mode.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\-l\fP
This option enables output logging.
When \f3dtterm\fP enables logging, all output received from the subprocess is 
logged either to a file or to a command pipeline (as specified via the \f3\-lf\fP 
option described below).
Since data are logged directly from the subprocess, the log file includes
all escape characters and carriage return/new line pairs the terminal
line discipline sends.
The appllication may enable and disable logging via escape sequences.
.P
.LI \f3\+l\fP
This option disables output logging.
This is the default.
.P
.LI "\f3\-lf\fP \f2file_name\fP"
This option specifies file name to which \f3dtterm\fP writes
output logging (described above).
If the filename begins with a pipe symbol
(``\f3|\fP''), \f3dtterm\fP assumes the rest of the string to be a command
to be used as the endpoint of a pipe.
If the filename ends in \f3XXXXX\fP, 
the last 5 characters will be replaced with the process ID of \f3dtterm\fP.
The default filename is \f3DttermLogXXXXX\fP
and is created in the directory
from which the subprocess was started.
.P
\f2file_name\fP - Specifies the log file name \f3dtterm\fP uses for logging.
.P
.LI \f3\-ls\fP
This option indicates that the shell that is started be a login
shell (that is, the first character of \f3argv[0]\fP
be a dash), indicating
to the shell that it read the system's \f3profile\fP
and the user's \f3.profile\fP
(for
.Cm ksh 1
and
.Cm sh 1,
or the system's \f3csh.login\fP and the user's \f3.login\fP 
(for
.Cm csh 1.
.P
.LI \f3\+ls\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP starts a normal (non-login) shell.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI \f3\-map\fP
This option indicates that \f3dtterm\fP map
(de-iconify) itself upon subprocess output if it is unmapped (iconified).
The user may specify, via the \f3mapOnOutputDelay\fP resource (described below),
an initial period of time during which \f3dtterm\fP does not map itself upon
subprocess output.
.P
.LI \f3\+map\fP
This option indicates there is no special mapping behavior.
This is the default.
.P
.LI \f3\-mb\fP
This option specifies that the bell rings
when the user types at a specified distance from the right margin.
The distance from the
right margin is specified by the \f3\-nb\fP option (described below).
.P
.LI \f3\+mb\fP
This option specifies that the bell not ring
when the user types near the right margin.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI "\f3\-ms\fP \f2pointer_color\fP"
This option specifies the foreground color \f3dtterm\fP uses for the terminal
window's (X11) pointer cursor.
The default is the terminal
window's foreground color (see \f3\-foreground\fP above).
.P
\f2pointer_color\fP - This option specifies the pointer foreground color \f3dtterm\fP
uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-name\fP \f2prog_name\fP"
Specifies the X11 name of the \f3dtterm\fP window.
.P
\f2prog_name\fP - Specifies the name to use.
.P
.LI "\f3\-nb\fP \f2number\fP"
This option specifies the number of characters from the right
margin at which the margin bell rings, when enabled.
The default is 10.
.P
\f2number\fP - Specifies the number of characters.
.P
.LI \f3\-rw\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP enables reverse-wraparound.
.P
.LI \+rw
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP does not enable reverse-wraparound.
This is the default.
.P
.LI "\f3\-S\fP \f2ccn\fP"
This option specifies that the terminal emulator is run against a
pre-opened pty or STREAMS device.
The terminal emulator provides this option to use where the pty or STREAMS device
name is of the form \f3tty??\fP (that is, exactly two characters following the 
\f3``tty''\fP).
This option is intended for use when \f3dtterm\fP is invoked
programatically from within another application.
.P
\f2cc\fP - Specifies the last two characters of the pty or STREAMS device's
slave name where the pty
slave name is of the form ``\f(CWtty??\fP''.
This value is ignored, but must be exactly two characters in length.
.P
.LI \f3n\fP
Specifies the number of the file descriptor that corresponds to the pty or STREAMS
device's already opened master side.
.P
.LI "\f3\-S\fP \f2c . n\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-S\fP\f2ccn\fP above,
but is provided for systems with a larger pty or STREAMS device name space.
.P
\f2c\fP - Specifies the last component of the pty or STREAMS device slave name.
The terminal emulator ignores this value and the value may be empty.
.P
\f2n\fP - Specifies the number of the file descriptor that corresponds to the pty or STREAMS device's
already opened master side.
.P
.LI \f3\-sb\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP display a scroll bar.
This is the default.
.P
.LI \f3\+sb\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP not display a scroll bar.
.P
.LI \f3\-sf\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP generate Sun Function Key escape codes
instead of standard VT220 escape sequences for the terminal's function keys.
.P
.LI \f3\+sf\fP
This option specifies that \f3dtterm\fP generate standard VT220 escape sequences
instead of Sun Function Key escape codes for the terminal's function keys.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI "\f3\-sl\fP \f2screens\fP[\f3s|l\fP]"
This option specifies the number of lines in the terminal buffer beyond the
length of the window.
The option value consists of a number followed by
an optional suffix.
If no suffix is included or the suffix is ``l'' (ell), the
total length of the terminal buffer is \f2screens\fP plus the length of
the terminal window.
If the suffix is ``s'' (ess) the total length of the
terminal buffer is \f2screens\fP plus one times the length of the
terminal window.
The \f3dtterm\fP utility tries to maintain the same buffer-to-window
ratio when the window is resized larger.
The default is ``4s''.
.P
\f2screens\fP - Specifies the number of screens or lines to save.
.P
.LI "\f3\-ti\fP \f2term_id\fP"
This option supplies the name \f3dtterm\fP uses to select the correct response to
terminal ID queries.
Valid values are \f3vt100\fP, \f3vt101\fP,
\f3vt102\fP, and \f3vt220\fP.
The default is \f3vt220\fP.
.P
\f2term_id\fP - Specifies the terminal ID to use.
.P
.LI "\f3\-title\fP \f2title_string\fP"
This option specifies the window title.
If the user uses the \f3-e\fP option, the
default is the last component of the program's path.
If the user does not use the \f3-e\fP option, the default is the last
component of the name used to execute \f3dtterm\fP (that is, \f3argv[0]\fP).
.P
\f2title_string\fP - Specifies the title \f3dterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI "\f3\-tm\fP \f2term_modes\fP"
This option specifies a string containing terminal-setting keywords
and the characters to which they are to be bound.
Allowable keywords
include:  \f3intr\fP, \f3quit\fP, \f3erase\fP, \f3kill\fP, \f3eof\fP,
\f3eol\fP, \f3swtch\fP, \f3start\fP, \f3stop\fP, \f3brk\fP,
\f3susp\fP, \f3dsusp\fP, \f3rprnt\fP, \f3flush\fP, \f3weras\fP,
and \f3lnext\fP.
The terminal emulator correctly parses and silently ignores keywords that do not apply
to a specific architecture.
Control characters may be specified as \f3^\fP\f2char\fP (two characters, 
`\f3^\fP'
followed by \f2char\fP).
The character \f2char\fP is case insensitive.
Some examples are: \f3^c\fP, \f3^C\fP, \f3^u\fP, and \f3^U\fP.
\f3^?\fP may be used to indicate delete.
This is very useful for overridding the default terminal settings without having to
do an \f3stty(1)\fP 
every time a terminal process is started.
The default is 
.Cn NULL .
.P
\f2term_modes\fP - Specifies the terminal mode string.
.P
.LI "\f3\-tn\fP \f2term_name\fP"
This option specifies a name \f3dtterm\fP uses to set the \f3TERM\fP
environment variable to.
The default is \f3vt220\fP.
.P
\2term_name\fP - Specifies the terminal name \f3dtterm\fP uses.
.P
.LI \f3\-usage\fP
Prints a usage message on the screen.
.P
.LI \f3\-vb\fP
This option indicates that a visual bell is preferred over an audible one.
Instead of ringing the
terminal bell whenever a Control-G is received, the window is flashed.
.P
.LI \f3\+vb\fP
This option indicates that an audio bell is preferred over an visual one.
This is the default behavior.
.P
.LI "\f3\-w\fP \f2border_width\fP"
This option is identical to \f3\-borderwidth\fP above.
.P
\f2border_width\fP - Specifies the width of the window border in pixels.
.P
.LI "\f3\-xrm\fP \f2resource_string\fP"
This option allows the user to specify the X11 Resource Manager-style
resources on the command line.
See the X11 documentation for more information.
.P
\f2resource_string\fP - Specifies an X11 resource string.
.LE
.P
