.P
.VL 6
.LI \f3allowSendEvents\fP
This resource specifies that the terminal emulator allow
synthetic events (generated and sent by another application).
Enabling this resource opens up a possible security hole.
The default is False.
.LI \f3appCursorDefault\fP
If True, the cursor keys are initially in application mode.
If False, the cursor keys are initially in cursor mode.
The default
is False.
.LI \f3appKeypadDefault\fP
If True, the keypad keys are initially in application mode.
If False, the keypad keys are initially in numeric mode.
The default
is False.
.LI \f3autoWrap\fP
This resource specifies whether or not auto-wraparound is initially
enabled.  The default is True.
.LI \f3background\fP
This resource specifies the
background color of the terminal window as well as the default background
color for the
scroll bar.
Under
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this resource defaults to either the primary
color set background
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
(default)
or select
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" (default)
pixel (see
\f3backgroundIsSelect\fP).
Without
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this resource defaults to black.
.LI \f3backgroundIsSelect\fP
This resource specifies that the terminal window should use the Motif
select color instead of the background color for the terminal window's
background color.  The default is False.
.LI \f3blinkRate\fP
This resource specifies the number of milliseconds the cursor is in the
``on'' and ``off'' states while blinking.
A 250 value blinks the cursor two times per second.
A 0 value turns blinking off.
The default is 250.
.LI \f3borderColor\fP
This resource specifies the border color for the window.
The window border
may not be visible when re-parenting window managers such as
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.Cm dtwm 1X
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" \f3vuewm(1X)\fP
and
.Cm mwm 1X
are used.
The default is black.
.LI \f3borderWidth\fP
This resource specifies the border width of the shell widget's window.
This value may be overridden by re-parenting window managers such as
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.Cm dtwm 1X
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" \f3vuewm(1X)\fP
and 
.Cm mwm 1X.
The default is 0.
.LI \f3c132\fP
This resource specifies whether or not the \f3DECCOLM\fP escape sequence that
switches between a 132 and 80 column window is honored.
The default is False.
.LI \f3charCursorStyle\fP
This resource specifies the shape of the text cursor.
A
.Cn charcursor_box
value specifies a cursor the width and height of the base
font's bounding box.
A
.Cn charcursor_bar
value specifies a cursor the
width of the base font's bounding box, 2 pixels high, and drawn with its
top on the baseline.
.\" DS - do we need to mention charcursor_invisible here????????
The default is
.Cn charcursor_box .
.LI \f3consoleMode\fP
This resource specifies that output directed at \f3/dev/console\fP
be directed instead to the terminal window.
It is provided as a way to
prevent output that would normally be displayed on the ITE from stepping
on the X server's display.
It is not provided as a general mechanism to
direct the output from an arbitrary system's 
\f3/dev/console\fP
to an arbitrary X server.
Ownership of, and read-write permission for,
\f3/dev/console\fP
is required to redirect console output.
The default is False.
.LI \f3foreground\fP
This resource specifies the foreground of the terminal window as well as
the default \f3dtterm\fP uses for the scroll bar and the color used for the pointer
cursor.
Under
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this resource defaults to the primary
color set foreground pixel.
Without
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal Cde string:
Cde,
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" HPVUE,
this resource defaults to
white.
.LI \f3geometry\fP
This resource specifies the terminal window's preferred size and position.
The default size is 24 lines of 80 characters each.
There is no default position.
.LI \f3halfBrightInhibit\fP
This resource specifies that \f3dtterm\fP not allocate or use half-bright colors
when displaying characters with the faint graphics rendition set.
In this mode \f3dtterm\fP allocates fewer read-only cells from the color map.
The default is False.
.LI \f3iconGeometry\fP
This resource specifies the preferred position of the terminal
emulator's icon.
Window managers (including
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal CDE string:
.Cm dtwm 1
.\" !!!! normal VUE string:
.\" .Cm vuewm 1X
and 
.Cm mwm 1X 
may ignore this value.
There is no default.
.LI \f3iconic\fP
This resource specifies whether or not the terminal emulator is initially
displayed in an iconified state.
The default is False.
.LI \f3iconName\fP
This resource specifies the name for the icon.
If the user uses \f3\-e\fP option, the default
is the last component of the program's path.
If the user does not use \f3\-e\fP option, the default is
the last component of the name
used to execute \f3dtterm\fP (that is, \f3argv[0]\fP).
.LI \f3jumpScroll\fP
This resource specifies that \f3dtterm\fP use jump scrolling.
Under jump
scrolling, the screen may be scrolled more than one line at a time.
This provides for faster screen updates when multiple lines of text are
sent to the terminal.
The maximum number of lines that may be
jump scrolled is limited to the number of lines in the terminal window.
The terminal emulator guarantees that all lines are displayed.
The default is True.
.LI \f3kshMode\fP
This resource enables ksh mode.
Under ksh
mode, a key pressed with the extend modifier bit set generates an
escape character followed by the character generated by the un-extended
keystroke.
This option is provided for use with emacs and the emacs
command line editor mode of
.Cm ksh 1 or
.Cm ied 1.
It conflicts with the
normal meta key use for generating extended single byte
characters and for generating multi-byte Asian characters.
The default
is False.
.LI \f3logging\fP
This resource enables output logging.
When logging is enabled, all
output received from the subprocess is logged either to a file or to a
command pipeline (as specified via the \f3logFile\fP option
below).
Since the data is logged directly from the subprocess, it includes all escape characters
and carriage return / new line pairs the terminal line discipline sends.
Logging may be enabled and disabled via escape sequences.
The default is False.
.LI \f3logFile\fP
This resource specifies the filename \f3dtterm\fP uses to write the output logging
(described above) to.
If the filename begins with a pipe symbol
(\f3|\fP), \f3dtterm\fP assumes 
the rest of the string is a command to be used as the
endpoint of a pipe.
If the filename ends in \f3XXXXX\fP , 
the
last 5 characters are replaced with the \f3dtterm\fP's process ID.
The default filename is \f3DttermLogXXXXX\fP
and is created in the directory from which the subprocess
was started.
.LI \f3logInhibit\fP
This resource indicates that \f3dtterm\fP inhibit device and file logging.
The default is False.
.LI \f3loginShell\fP
This resource indicates that the shell that is started be a login
shell (that is, the first character of \f3argv[0] \fP
is a dash, indicating
that the shell should read the system's \f3profile\fP
and the user's \f3.profile \fP (for \f3ksh\fP and \f3sh\fP)
or the system \f3csh.login \fP and the user's \f3.login \fP
(for \f3csh\fP)).
The default is False.
.LI \f3mapOnOutput\fP
This resource indicates that the terminal emulator map
(de-iconify) itself upon subprocess output if it is unmapped (iconified).
The user may specify, via the \f3mapOnOutputDelay\fP resource (described below),
an initial period of time during which \f3dtterm\fP does not map itself
upon subprocess output.
The default is False.
.LI \f3mapOnOutputDelay\fP
This resource specifies the number of seconds after start-up that \f3dtterm\fP
does not honor the \f3mapOnOutput\fP resource (described above).
This allows the application to send
initial output (for example, shell prompts) to the terminal without
auto mapping the window.
The default is 0 (no delay).
.LI \f3marginBell\fP
This resource specifies whether or not the bell rings when the user types near
the right margin.
The distance from the right margin is specified by
the \f3nMarginBell\fP resource (described below).
The default is False.
.LI \f3menu\fP
This resource indicates that \f3dtterm\fP display a pulldown menu bar.
The
default is True.
.LI \f3nMarginBell\fP
This resource specifies the number of characters from the right margin at which the
margin bell rings, when enabled.
The default is 10.
.LI \f3pointerBlank\fP
This resource indicates that \f3dtterm\fP put the pointer cursor into
blanking mode.
In this mode, the cursor turns on when the pointer
is moved, and is blanked either after a selectable number of
seconds or after keyboard input.
The \f3pointerBlankDelay\fP resource (described below) sets the delay.
The default is False.
.LI \f3pointerBlankDelay\fP
This resource specifies the number of seconds to wait after the pointer
has stopped moving before blanking the pointer (see \f3pointerBlank\fP above).
A 0 value delays pointer blanking until a key is pressed.
The default is 2 seconds.
.LI \f3pointerColor\fP
This resource specifies the foreground color \f3dtterm\fP uses for the terminal
window's pointer (X11) cursor.
The default is the terminal window's foreground color (see \f3foreground\fP above).
.LI \f3pointerColorBackground\fP
This resource specifies the background color \f3dtterm\fP uses for the terminal
window's pointer (X11) cursor.
The default is the terminal window's background color (see \f3background\fP above).
.LI \f3pointerShape\fP
This resource specifies the X cursor font character \f3dtterm\fP uses as the
pointer cursor.
The font character should be specified as a string from the include file \f3<X11/cursorfont.h>\fP
with the leading \f3\s-1XC_\s0\fP removed.
The default is \f3xterm\fP.
.LI \f3reverseWrap\fP
This resource specifies whether or not reverse-wraparound is
enabled.
The default is False.
.LI \f3saveLines\fP
This resource specifies the number lines in the terminal buffer beyond the
length of the window.
This resource value consists of a number followed by
an options suffix.
If no suffix is included or the suffix is ``l'' (ell), the
total length of the terminal buffer is \f2screens\fP plus the length of
the terminal window.
If the suffix is ``s'' (ess) the total length of the
terminal buffer is (\f2screens\fP plus one) times the length of the
terminal window.
The \f3dtterm\fP utility tries to maintain the same buffer-to-window
ratio when the window is resized larger.
The default is ``4s''.
.LI \f3scrollBar\fP
This resources indicates that \f3dtterm\fP displaya scroll bar.
The default is False.
.LI \f3sunFunctionKeys\fP
This resource specifies whether or not \f3dtterm\fP generates Sun Function Key
escape codes instead of standard VT220 escape
sequences for the terminal's function keys.
The default is False.
.LI \f3termId\fP
This resource supplies the name used to select the correct response to
terminal ID queries.
Valid values are \f3vt100\fP, \f3vt101\fP, \f3vt102\fP, and
\f3vt220\fP.
The default is \f3vt220\fP.
.LI \f3termName\fP
This resource specifies a name \f3dtterm\fP sets the \f3TERM\fP environment variable to.
The default is \f3vt220\fP.
.LI \f3title\fP
This resource specifies the window title.
If the uses uses the \f3\-e\fP option, the
default is the last component of the program's path.
If the user does not use the \f3\-e\fP
option, the default is the last component of the name
used to execute \f3dtterm\fP (that is, \f3argv[0]\fP).
.LI \f3ttyModes\fP
This resource specifies a string containing terminal-setting keywords
and the characters to which they are to be bound.
Allowable keywords
include:  \f3intr\fP, \f3quit\fP, \f3erase\fP, \f3kill\fP, \f3eof\fP, \f3eol\fP, 
\f3swtch\fP, \f3start\fP, \f3stop\fP, \f3brk\fP,
\f3susp\fP, \f3dsusp\fP, \f3rprnt\fP, \f3flush\fP, \f3weras\fP, and \f3lnext\fP.
The terminal emulator correctly parses and silently ignores keywords that
do not apply to a specific architecture.
Control characters may be specified as \f3^\fP\f2char\fP (two characters, 
`\f3^\fP'
followed by \f2char\fP).
The character \f2char\fP is case insensitive.
Some examples are: ``\f3^c\fP'', ``\f3^C\fP'', ``\f3^u\fP'', and ``\f3^U\fP''.
``\f3^?\fP'' may be used to indicate delete.
This is useful for overriding the
default terminal settings without having to do an \f3stty \fP
every time a terminal process is started.
The default is
.Cn NULL .
.LI \f3userBoldFont\fP
This resource specifies an \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses when displaying bold
terminal text.
It should be specified as a Motif
.Fn XmFontList 3X.
The terminal emulator supports only character- or mono-spaced fonts.
When using proportional fonts, the behavior is undefined.
The terminal emulator generates a default bold font based on the \f3XLFD\fP
name of the \f3userFont\fP.
If that font is not available, \f3dtterm\fP generates bold text
by overstriking (with a one pixel offset) the \f3userFont\fP.
.LI \f3userFont\fP
This resource specifies an \f3XFontSet\fP \f3dtterm\fP uses when displaying terminal
text.
\f3XFontSet\fP should be specified as a Motif
.Fn XmFontList 3X.
The terminal emulator supports only character- or mono-spaced fonts.
When using proportional fonts, the behavior is undefined.
This font is not used
to display non-terminal text (menu bar, popup menu, dialog, etc.).
The default is
the \f3XmNtextFontList\fP value of the parent bulletin board (see
.Fn XmBulletinBoard 3X)
in the same manner as the
.Fn XmText 3X
widget.
.LI \f3visualBellfP
This resource indicates that a visual bell is preferred over an audible
one.
Instead of ringing the terminal bell whenever a Control-G is
received, the window is flashed.
The default is False.
.LE
.P
