.SH ENVIRONMENT
.P
The terminal emulator recognizes the following environment variables:
.VL 6
.LI \f3XUSERFILESEARCHPATH\fP
The \f3XUSERFILESEARCHPATH\fP environment variable controls
where X applications look for their app-defaults resource files.
The default is located in the directory
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal motif path:
.\" \f3/usr/lib/X11/app-defaults\fP.
.\" !!!! normal CDE path:
\f3/usr/dt/app-defaults\fP.
You need to set \f3XUSERFILESEARCHPATH\fP if your resource
files are not in this location.
.LI \f3XFILESEARCHPATH\fP
The environment variable \f3XFILESEARCHPATH\fP may define a
language-dependent location of app-defaults.
.LI \f3XENVIRONMENT\fP
The user may specify any user and machine-specific resources by setting the
\f3XENVIRONMENT\fP environment variable to the name of a resource file
to be loaded by all applications.
If this variable is not defined, \f3dtterm\fP looks for a file named 
\f3$HOME/.Xdefaults-hostname\fP instead,
where hostname is the name of the host where the application is
executing.
.LI \f3XMODIFIER\fP
This environment variable allows the user to specify which input method to use.
.LI \f3LANG\fP
The user must set the \f3LANG\fP environment variable in order to use native
language support.
Setting \f3LANG\fP causes X to use the
language-sensitive routines for character handling.
.LI \f3NLSPATH\fP
The \f3NLSPATH\fP environment variable determines the paths
applications search for NLS message catalogs.
X clients place NLS message catalogs in the
.\" !!!! version/config dependent string
.\" !!!! normal pre-SVR5 path:
.\" \f3/usr/lib/nls/$LANG\fP
.\" !!!! normal CDE path:
\f3/usr/dt/lib/nls/$LANG\fP
directory.
The user must set both
\f3LANG\fP and \f3NLSPATH\fP in order to use
these message catalogs.
.LI \f3XAPPLRESDIR\fP
This environment variable allows the user to name a directory that
contains application specific resources.
If this environment variable
exists, and is set to an existing directory, then it is searched (in
addition to the standard locations) for files containing application
specific resource specifications.
.LI \f3HOME\fP
The terminal emulator uses this environment variable to
determine the location of configuration files.
.LI \f3SHELL\fP
Default application to run.
.LI \f3TERM\fP
The terminal emulator sets the subprocess's \f3TERM\fP environment
variable to the \f3termName\fP resource value.
Applications use this variable to determine the type of escape sequences to use
when driving the terminal emulator.
.LI \f3LINES\fP
The terminal emulator sets the subprocess's \f3LINES\fP
environment variable to the number of lines present in the terminal
window at creation.
If the size of the terminal window is subsequently
changed, the terminal emulator uses the \f3TIOCSWINSZ\fP ioctl to
inform the applications running against it of the new line count.
Under normal use, the user's shell updates
\f3LINES\fP with the updated value.
.LI \f3COLUMNS\fP
The terminal emulator sets the subprocess's \f3COLUMNS\fP
environment variable to the number of columns present in the terminal
window at creation.
If the size of the terminal window is subsequently
changed the terminal emulator will use the \f3TIOCSWINSZ\fP ioctl to
inform the applications running against it of the new column count.
Under normal use, the user's shell will update \f3COLUMNS\fP with the
updated value.
.LI \f3DISPLAY\fP
This environment variable specifies the default X11 display to connect
to (see \f3\-display\fP above).
The terminal emulator will set the
subprocess's \f3DISPLAY\fP environment variable to the connected X11
display name.
.LI \f3WINDOWID\fP
The terminal emulator sets the subprocess's \f3WINDOWID\fP
environment variable to the window number of the window in which text
will be rendered.
.LI \f3TERMINAL_EMULATOR\fP
This environment variable is set to \f3dtterm\fP to indicate that
the process is running from a terminal emulator.
.LE
.P
